{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b19f3ea5-0032-4bc7-8831-7bf1d1a56d13","content":"The standard .NET approach is to use the **`System.IO.Abstractions`** NuGet package. It wraps the static `System.IO` calls behind injectable interfaces.\n\n**Steps:**\n1. `dotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions`\n2. Replace direct calls with the interface:\n   ```csharp\n   // Before\n   File.WriteAllText(path, content);\n\n   // After — inject IFileSystem via constructor\n   public MyService(IFileSystem fileSystem) => _fs = fileSystem;\n   _fs.File.WriteAllText(path, content);\n   ```\n3. In production, register `new FileSystem()`. In tests, use `MockFileSystem` from `System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers`:\n   ```csharp\n   var fs = new MockFileSystem();\n   var svc = new MyService(fs);\n   ```\n\nThis covers `IFile.WriteAllText`, `IFile.ReadAllText`, `IDirectory.Exists`, and the rest of `System.IO` — no custom wrapper needed.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a9b684f2-91b1-4133-8b0c-f507eb964ee3","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about making file system operations testable in .NET. This is a general software engineering question about testability patterns, not a codebase-specific task. I should provide a concise, helpful answer.\n\nThe standard approach in .NET is to use `System.IO.Abstractions` — a well-known NuGet package that provides interfaces (`IFileSystem`, `IFile`, `IDirectory`) wrapping `System.IO` static methods. This lets you inject a mock/fake file system in tests.\n\nLet me give a concise answer.","outputTokens":390,"requestId":"1BCE:19082:99751D:ADCC7A:6A03E95E"},"id":"1bfd2178-ba1a-45da-af11-35e6adac3f86","timestamp":"2026-05-13T03:00:56.088Z","parentId":"a11d6bee-495b-4ff0-8ad1-65352aa5ba35"}
